          "body": "The psalm's final verse is the most theologically compressed sentence in the chapter: 'Salvation belongs to the LORD; Your blessing be upon Your people.' Yeshuah — the very word the enemies used as a taunt in verse 2 ('there is no yeshuah in God') — is now declared God's exclusive possession. The enemy's denial becomes the psalmist's doxology. This is not triumphalism; the rescue may not yet have come. David is still surrounded. But the ownership of salvation has been settled, and that settlement is the basis for both the petition of v.7 and the doxology of v.8. Notably, the psalm ends by widening from the individual to the community: 'Your blessing be upon Your people.' David's personal lament becomes intercessory. His own deliverance, when it comes, will be a blessing that flows outward to the covenant people. This is the canonical pattern: the suffering of the individual anointed one, vindicated by God, becomes a source of blessing for the many — a typological pointer, in a context John Calvin recognized, toward the greater Son of David whose lament (Psalm 22) and vindication (Psalm 24) flow outward to all who belong to God."
