        "range": "3:1-2",
        "excerpt": "O LORD, how my adversaries have increased! Many are rising up against me. Many are saying of my soul, 'There is no deliverance for him in God.'",
        "body": "The psalm opens in medias res — David is already surrounded. The superscription supplies the historical frame: this is the moment of Absalom's rebellion (2 Samuel 15-17), when a son David loved turned the hearts of Israel against him, and the king fled Jerusalem weeping, barefoot, his head covered (2 Samuel 15:30). The crisis is as personal and political as any David faced. The verb 'have increased' (*ravav*) and the noun 'how many' (*rav*) repeat in the space of two verses to drive the numerical overwhelm home: David is not facing isolated opposition but a mass defection.\n\nBut the second verse introduces a weapon more dangerous than military force: theological accusation. 'Many are saying of my soul, there is no deliverance for him in God.' The Hebrew *nephesh* — often translated 'soul' — here means something like 'of him' or 'concerning his life'; the enemies are passing judgment on David's standing before God. Their verdict is that God has abandoned him. This is the satanic logic that reappears at the cross: 'He trusts in God; let God rescue him' (Matthew 27:43, echoing Psalm 22:8). The cruelest assault on the believer is not violence but the claim that God has gone silent.\n\nThe Selah after verse 2 is the psalm's first structural marker — a pause that holds the worshiper fully inside the worst claim before allowing the pivot. This is pastorally intentional. Lament requires the full articulation of the problem before the turn to God. Psalmic spirituality does not rush to comfort; it names the weight before it lifts it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsar* (adversaries, v.1) — from a root meaning to press or squeeze; the oppressive constriction of being besieged. *Yeshuah* (deliverance, v.2) — the same lemma that returns in v.8 as 'salvation belongs to the LORD' — the taunt and the doxology share a word."
