        "excerpt": "But You, O LORD, are a shield about me, My glory, and the One who lifts my head. I was crying to the LORD with my voice, and He answered me from His holy mountain.",
        "body": "The psalm's decisive turn arrives in two Hebrew words: *we'attah Yehovah* — 'But You, O LORD.' The adversarial 'many' of verses 1-2 meets the singular 'You' of the covenant God. The entire complaint is answered not by a report of rescue but by a direct address that reframes who the central actor is. David does not wait for the crisis to resolve before confessing trust — he confesses trust in the middle of it. This is the psalm's chief lesson for prayer: the confession precedes the experience of relief.\n\nThree titles follow in rapid succession. The *shield* (*magen*) is not a body-shield covering part of David but an encircling defense — 'about me,' *baad*, literally 'surrounding, on behalf of.' The word is used of God as shield to Abram in Genesis 15:1, connecting David's crisis to the foundational covenant with the patriarchs. The *glory* (*kavod*) — weight, honor, splendor — relocates the source of David's worth from his royal office (which Absalom has temporarily seized) to the divine relationship (which cannot be seized). When earthly dignity is stripped, 'my glory' remains if God is its source. Spurgeon wrote of this title: 'He that has God for his glory has a glory that cannot be stripped from him by any earthly force.'\n\nThe third title — 'the One who lifts my head' (*merim roshi*) — reverses the shame posture of the defeated. In ancient Near Eastern iconography, the conquered king was forced to prostrate with head bowed before the conqueror's foot. David confesses that the LORD will do what the enemy has tried to prevent: restore his head to its upright, honored position. The same expression appears in Genesis 40:13 (Pharaoh 'lifting the head' of the restored cupbearer) and in 2 Kings 25:27 (Jehoiachin's head lifted in Babylonian exile).\n\nVerse 4 then supplies the ground: 'I was crying to the LORD with my voice, and He answered me from His holy mountain.' This is not a hope but a past event. The answer has already come. God's holy mountain — Zion, from which David fled — is still the seat of divine response. No political reversal has displaced the divine King from His throne.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Magen baad* — 'shield surrounding' — baad implies encircling, covering on all sides, not merely from one direction. *Kavod* — the weightiness, worth, and honor-claim of a person's standing; here assigned entirely to the divine relationship, not the royal office."
