        "body": "Verses 5-6 are the psalm's most intimate movement and its most counterintuitive claim. David does not report a military victory or a diplomatic resolution; he reports that he slept. In the open wilderness, surrounded by tens of thousands, the king of Israel lay down, closed his eyes, and woke up. Three sequential Hebrew verbs carry the weight: *shakhav* (lay down), *yashen* (slept), *quts* (awoke). The sequence is deliberately ordinary — this is the daily rhythm of a person who trusts. You cannot manufacture sleep in genuine danger; it comes only when something in you has released the outcome to another.\n\nThe explanation David gives is also the logical basis: 'for the LORD sustains me' (*ki Yehovah yismekeni*). *Samakh* — to uphold, support, prop up — is the word for leaning one's weight on a staff or on the LORD. David's unconscious hours were not unguarded; the LORD held him through them. This transforms sleep from vulnerability into testimony. Every morning David woke was a small resurrection, a daily proof of continued divine care. Psalm 4:8 will state the same truth explicitly: 'In peace I will both lie down and sleep, for You alone, O LORD, make me to dwell in safety.'\n\nVerse 6 draws the direct inference from the night's experience: 'I will not be afraid of ten thousands of people who have set themselves against me round about.' The imperfect tense projects the trust built by past experience (the answered prayer of v.4, the sustained sleep of v.5) forward into the ongoing threat. The quantitative language — 'ten thousands... round about' — echoes the complaint of verses 1-2 but now meets a different response. The numbers have not changed. What has changed is the category within which David holds them: the LORD who sustained him through the night is larger than any encirclement.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Revavah* (ten thousands, v.6) — the same root as *ravav* (have increased, v.1) and *rav* (many, vv.1-2). The verbal echo is intentional: the numerical overwhelm of the complaint reappears in the confession of fearlessness, demonstrating that the numbers themselves have not moved David — what has moved is his relationship to them."
