        "excerpt": "Arise, O LORD; save me, O my God! For You have smitten all my enemies on the cheek; You have shattered the teeth of the wicked.",
        "body": "With verse 7, David turns from confession to direct petition — but the petition is not wishful. It is grounded in two perfect-tense verbs that reach either into David's prior history of deliverance or employ the prophetic perfect, speaking future certainty as accomplished fact. Either reading arrives at the same pastoral logic: the petition 'save me' is anchored in 'You have already acted this way before.' Prayer in the Psalms is not leverage but remembrance — invoking who God has shown Himself to be.\n\nThe imperative 'Arise, O LORD' (*qumah Yehovah*) draws on the ancient battle-cry of Numbers 10:35: 'Rise up, O LORD! And let Your enemies be scattered.' The verb *qamay* (rise up) appeared in verse 1 describing the enemies who rise against David; now it is petitioned of the LORD. The reversal is the prayer's entire argument: let the one who truly rises be the LORD, not the enemy. Peter Craigie (Word Biblical Commentary, Psalms 1-50) notes that this cry was likely part of Israel's liturgical vocabulary for times of national emergency — David is not inventing new language but reaching into the covenant community's prayer-tradition.\n\nThe imagery of striking the cheek and shattering the teeth is judicial and symbolic, not sadistic. The cheek-blow is the instrument of contemptuous assault (cf. Lamentations 3:30; Micah 5:1); the teeth are the instruments of the taunt — the open mouths that said 'there is no deliverance for him in God' (v.2). God's judgment removes both the power to harm and the power to lie. Derek Kidner (Tyndale OT Commentary) observes that this is the language of the defeated adversary rendered powerless before the King's verdict — David prays for judicial silence upon those whose theological accusation has done its worst.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qumah* (arise) in v.7 and *qamay* (rise up) in v.1 — the same root inverted. Enemies who rose against David → prayer that the LORD would rise against them. *Nakhah* (strike, smite) and *shavar* (shatter, break) are both vivid verbs of decisive, irreversible action — not wounding but rendering powerless."
