        "excerpt": "Salvation belongs to the LORD; Your blessing be upon Your people!",
        "body": "The psalm's final verse is a theological summary that answers its own opening taunt. The enemies declared in verse 2 that there is no *yeshuah* (salvation) for David in God. David declares in verse 8 that *yeshuah* belongs to the LORD entirely — not partially, not conditionally, but as a sovereign possession. The word that the enemy wielded as a weapon becomes the doxology's subject. This is the psalm's most compressed argument: the same word that named the crisis in verse 2 names the resolution in verse 8, and what changed between them is not David's circumstances but David's orientation — away from the many who taunted and toward the One who saves.\n\nIt is significant that the psalm does not close with a report of rescue. The enemies are still there. The military situation is unchanged. What has changed is the theological verdict: salvation is the LORD's to give, and David has entrusted himself to the one who owns it. This is precisely the structure of faith commended throughout the New Testament — not sight, not the experienced rescue, but the confident assignment of the outcome to the One who holds it (Hebrews 11:1; Romans 4:18-21).\n\nThe final phrase — 'Your blessing be upon Your people' — widens the psalm from individual lament to communal intercession. David's personal crisis becomes a platform for petition on behalf of the entire covenant community. The same movement appears at the end of Psalm 22, where the individual sufferer's vindication opens into the universal proclamation: 'They will come and will declare His righteousness to a people who will be born' (Psalm 22:31). Calvin recognized the typological trajectory: the pattern of the suffering, trusting, vindicated anointed one who mediates blessing to the people anticipates the greater Son of David, whose lament (Psalm 22), sustained sleep in the tomb (Psalm 3:5 read through the resurrection lens of Acts 2:27-28), and vindication flow outward as blessing to all who are called His people.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yeshuah* — salvation, deliverance, spaciousness — appears in v.2 as taunt and v.8 as doxology; the same word, the same God, the reversed verdict. *Berakhah* (blessing) is the outflow of divine favor toward the community — the individual's salvation is never the terminus but always the fountain."
